\f1\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\tx560\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 A 
\f0\b nephron 
\f1\b0 is the single, functional unit of a kidney. There are four main processes that occur in the nephron: \cb1 \
\cb3 1. Filtration\cb1 \
\cb3 2. Reabsorption \
3. Secretion\cb1 \
\cb3 4. Excretion \cb1 \
\
\
\pard\tx560\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs48 \cf4 \cb3 Filtration 
\f1\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Filtration occurs in cortex at the 
\f0\b renal corpuscle 
\f1\b0 which consists of the 
\f0\b glomerulus 
\f1\b0 and the 
\f0\b Bowman\'92s capsule. 
\f1\b0 Blood enters from the 
\f2\i afferent arteriole 
\f1\i0 into the glomerulus which acts as a sieve. 
\f0\b Podocytes 
\f1\b0 from the Bowman\'92s capsule surround the glomerulus to form 
\f0\b fenestrations 
\f1\b0 allowing small substances (water and solutes) to be filtered into the Bowman\'92s capsule while larger substances (proteins and blood cells) remain in the blood. The glomerulus exits the Bowman\'92s capsule via the 
\f2\i efferent arteriole 
\f1\i0 which goes on to form the 
\f0\b peritubular capillaries
\f1\b0 . \cb1 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs48 \cf4 \cb3 Reabsorption 
\f1\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Throughout the nephron, water and solutes that the body needs are reabsorbed from the filtrate back into the blood.\cb1 \
\cb3 The 
\f0\b loop of Henle 
\f1\b0 descends into the medulla and has selective permeability. It is surrounded by the 
\f0\b vasa recta 
\f1\b0 (capillaries running parallel to the loop of Henle). 
\f2\i Water 
\f1\i0 is reabsorbed into the blood as the filtrate travels down the 
\f0\b descending limb 
\f1\b0 (filtrate becomes more concentrated) and 
\f2\i solutes 
\f1\i0 are reabsorbed as the filtrate travels up the 
\f0\b ascending limb 
\f1\b0 (filtrate becomes less concentrated). \cb1 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs48 \cf4 \cb3 Secretion 
\f1\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Secretion is the transfer of solutions from the blood vasculature directly into the nephron tubule filtrate. This occurs at the 
\f0\b distal convoluted tubule 
\f1\b0 and the 
\f0\b proximal convoluted tubule. 
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs48 \cf4 \cb3 Excretion 
\f1\b0\fs36 \cf2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The filtrate (now urine) travels from the\cb1  \cb3 nephrons to the 
\f0\b collecting duct 
\f1\b0 which leads to the 
\f0\b renal pelvis 
\f1\b0 and then to the 
\f0\b ureter.\cb1  
\f1\b0 \cb3 The ureter connects the kidney to the 
\f0\b bladder 
\f1\b0 where urine is stored. When the signal is received, urine is excreted from the bladder and the body via the 
\f0\b urethra. 
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

